│ stop({"edit_points": [[486, 491, "llvm/lib/Transforms/Utils/Local.cpp"]],     │
│ "thoughts": "1. Understanding the Issue:\nThe crash occurs inside InstCombine │
│ when checking whether an instruction is trivially dead. Specifically,         │
│ Value::materialized_use_begin() asserts that hasUseList() is true, but it's   │
│ being called on a Value that does not maintain a use-list (notably            │
│ PoisonValue). This happens during analysis of lifetime intrinsics.\n\n2.      │
│ Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe log shows InstCombine visiting the alloca, then     │
│ store to %arg, then store to poison. It replaces the alloca with ptr poison   │
│ and erases the alloca. Immediately after, the pass calls                      │
│ isInstructionTriviallyDead() on subsequent instructions, which triggers       │
│ wouldInstructionBeTriviallyDead(). That function enters the lifetime          │
│ intrinsic case and tries to iterate over uses of the pointer argument via     │
│ Arg->uses(). The backtrace matches Local.cpp:487, which is precisely the      │
│ lifetime case iterating uses. The crash happens at Value::uses() because the  │
│ Value (poison) lacks a materialized use-list.\n\n3. Root Cause                │
│ Analysis:\nwouldInstructionBeTriviallyDead() assumes that the pointer operand │
│ to llvm.lifetime.start/end has a materialized use list and iterates           │
│ Arg->uses() to check if all users are LifetimeIntrinsic. This assumption is   │
│ false for PoisonValue (and potentially other Values that don't maintain use   │
│ lists). InstCombine replaced the alloca with ptr poison, making the           │
│ lifetime.end's pointer argument be poison. Subsequently,                      │
│ wouldInstructionBeTriviallyDead() calls Arg->uses(), which asserts because    │
│ hasUseList() is false on PoisonValue.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\nModify   │
│ wouldInstructionBeTriviallyDead() lifetime-intrinsic branch to guard against  │
│ Values without a use-list. If the pointer argument doesn't have a use-list,   │
│ then its users aren't tracked; in this context, the only known user is the    │
│ current lifetime intrinsic. That satisfies the \"only uses are lifetime       │
│ intrinsics\" condition, so we can conservatively treat the intrinsic as dead. │
│ Concretely:\n\n- File: llvm/lib/Transforms/Utils/Local.cpp\n- Lines:          │
│ 486-491\n- Change the block under II->isLifetimeStartOrEnd() to first check   │
│ Arg->hasUseList(). If false, return true; otherwise iterate Arg->uses() as    │
│ before.\n\nEdit:\n\nReplace:\n  if (II->isLifetimeStartOrEnd()) {\n    auto   │
│ *Arg = II->getArgOperand(1);\n    // If the only uses of the alloca are       │
│ lifetime intrinsics, then the\n    // intrinsics are dead.\n    return        │
│ llvm::all_of(Arg->uses(), [](Use &Use) {\n      return                        │
│ isa<LifetimeIntrinsic>(Use.getUser());\n    });\n  }\n\nWith:\n  if           │
│ (II->isLifetimeStartOrEnd()) {\n    auto *Arg = II->getArgOperand(1);\n    // │
│ If the only uses of the pointer are lifetime intrinsics, then the\n    //     │
│ intrinsics are dead. Some Values (e.g. poison) do not maintain a\n    //      │
│ materialized use-list; in that case, the only known user here is this\n    // │
│ intrinsic, so treat it as dead.\n    if (!Arg->hasUseList())\n      return    │
│ true;\n    return llvm::all_of(Arg->uses(), [](Use &Use) {\n      return      │
│ isa<LifetimeIntrinsic>(Use.getUser());\n    });\n  }\n\n5. Conclusion:\nBy    │
│ guarding the uses() iteration with hasUseList() and returning true when the   │
│ pointer operand lacks a use-list, we avoid the assertion on Values like       │
│ PoisonValue and correctly treat lifetime intrinsics as dead when their        │
│ pointer operand has no tracked non-lifetime users. This resolves the crash in │
│ InstCombine for the provided reproducer without affecting correctness of      │
│ dead-code elimination decisions."})                                           │
